## Accept
The architecture **"one live example for belief, one pilot brief for delegation, one leave-behind for transfer"** is accepted as the final frame. The second canonical example moves to the leave-behind. The pilot brief becomes the delegable artifact. The four questions remain the in-room conceptual spine.

## Risk closure

**Risk A: Can the pilot brief be explained fast enough?**

Yes, if it is introduced as the *written form of the four questions*, not as a new artifact. The brief has six fields: task, owner, verifier, data boundary, sources, acceptance criteria. Four of those map directly onto the four questions; the other two (owner, data boundary) are the governance overlay. Introduce it once on screen at minute 14, partially filled from the live demo, with one sentence: *"This is what the four questions look like when a team writes them down before launching."* No new vocabulary, no new framework. Total airtime: ~90 seconds.

