Topic:
# Concepts vs concrete manipulations in the SSI cours

**Context.** A 30-minute workshop for executives of French PME/ETI (50–500 employees) who want to pilot AI-agent adoption in their teams. The course teaches the "SSI" framework (segmentation, external memory, repositories, packaging — proposer/verifier pattern, acceptance criteria). The tool used in the demo is Cowork (Claude's desktop app), but the framework is meant to be tool-agnostic (also applies to Claude Code, Codex CLI). Two canonical examples carry the framework: (1) a 15–25 page strategic memo from heterogeneous sources; (2) a reusable workflow that automates a recurring task. Audience are not developers.

**The question.** Should the cours teach a set of explicit concepts (the SSI framework, named and explained), or should it just encourage and walk through concrete manipulations (do this, then this, then this) and let the concepts emerge implicitly?

**The tension.**
- **Concepts as spine:** survives tool changes (the f

Transcript:
## Round 1 — Agent A

# Proposing side: Burn the framework slide. Teach one *failure-then-fix* loop where the exec plays verifier.

## Question the premise first
- "Concepts vs manipulations" is a false binary built for *trainers*, not learners. Both options assume the spine is **what you transmit**. For 30-min exec audiences the spine is **what they feel themselves doing**.
- SSI is not knowledge to be installed. It's a set of moves that only make sense once you've been bitten by their absence. Teaching the named framework first is like explaining seatbelts before anyone has crashed.
- The real risk in this room isn't "they forget the acronym." It's **"they conclude AI agents are unreliable toys"** because they watched a clean demo and have no model for why their own first try will fail. Concepts-first guarantees this outcome.

## My position: Manipulations-as-spine, but the manipulation is *catching the agent failing*
- Spine = a single 18-minute loop where you (a) launch a deliberately under-specified task, (b) let it visibly drift or hallucinate, (c) hand the exec the verifier seat, (d) fix it by adding exactly one SSI move, (e) re-run, (f) name the move *after* it worked.
- The concept lands as a **debrief label on a felt event**, not as a slide. "What we just did when we split the memo into 4 briefs — that's *segmentation*." Three seconds. No slide. They will remember it because their nervous system was engaged when it happened.
- Each of S/S/I gets one such moment. Four moments × ~5 min = the whole 30-min slot, including a 4-min cold open and a 2-min "what to try Monday."

## Minimum viable explicitation (earns its place)
- **One artifact only**: a single index card / one-slide cheat-sheet handed out at minute 28, listing the 4 moves with the *demo moment* next to each ("remember when X happened? That's Y"). Anchored to lived memory, not abstract definition.
- **One sentence at the open**, not a framework: *"In 30 minutes you'll do the verifier job four times. Each time you'll feel one missing piece. Those four pieces are what you'll deploy in your team Monday."* That's the entire conceptual contract. No taxonomy.
- **Zero slides labeled "SSI Framework."** If the slide exists, execs will photograph it and never run the loop. The framework must be *unphotographable* until minute 28.

## Why concepts-as-spine loses this room specifically
- French PME/ETI execs in a 30-min slot are pattern-matching for **"is this real or is this consulting deck theater?"** A named framework on slide 2 triggers the theater detector. You lose them in 90 seconds and never get them back.
- Transfer vocabulary is real, but it transfers *from concrete prior experience*, not from abstract priors. An exec who has watched themselves catch a hallucinated revenue figure and add an acceptance criterion has a vocabulary. An exec who has heard "proposer/verifier pattern" defined does not.
- Tool-agnosticism is a teacher's worry. Execs don't care that SSI outlives Cowork; they care that *something works Monday*. The transfer happens because the **move** is portable, not because the **noun** is portable. The noun is a coat hook for the move.

## Concrete 30-min spine (radical version)
- **0:00–4:00 — Cold open / public failure.** Run the memo task with no SSI. Let it produce a confident, wrong, generic 4-page draft. Don't comment. Let the silence land.
- **4:00–9:00 — Segmentation moment.** Exec in the room picks which 4 sub-briefs the memo actually needs. Re-run. Visibly better. Name it: "segmentation." Move on.
- **9:00–14:00 — External memory moment.** Drop in the 3 source PDFs the first run hallucinated around. Re-run a sub-brief. Name it. Move on.
- **14:00–20:00 — Repository moment (the workflow example).** Save the prompt + the acceptance criteria as a reusable artifact. Exec re-runs it on a *different* input live. Name it.
- **20:00–26:00 — Packaging / proposer-verifier.** Exec receives the agent's output and is asked out loud: "Do you accept this? On what criteria?" They will struggle. That struggle *is* the lesson. Name it.
- **26:00–28:00 — The card.** Hand out the one-pager. Four moves, four demo memories.
- **28:00–30:00 — Monday.** "Pick one recurring task in your org. Run it once with no SSI. Then add segmentation. Email me what changed." Done.

## Tradeoffs I'm accepting
- **Risk:** an exec who misses the debrief sentence walks out with moves but no vocabulary. Mitigation: the card.
- **Risk:** looks less "rigorous" to a buyer expecting a framework deck. Counter: send the framework PDF *after* the session as the leave-behind. Pre-session framework = theater detector trips; post-session framework = "ah, now I see what I did."
- **Risk:** demo failure looks unprofessional. Counter: **the staged failure is the product.** Executives who have only seen polished AI demos are the ones who pilot badly. Showing controlled failure is the single most valuable 4 minutes in the slot.

## The radical reframe I'd push hardest
- Stop calling it a *cours*. It's a **supervised first verifier shift.** The exec's job in the room is not to learn SSI; it's to *be the verifier four times*. SSI is the post-hoc name for what good verifiers do. Sell the seat, not the syllabus.

## Round 1 — Agent B

The proposal is strong on engagement, but it overcorrects. It turns the course into a controlled stunt and under-serves the actual executive job.

**Core Objection**

Execs are not there to become better live operators in Cowork. They are there to decide how their teams should pilot agents without creating chaos. That requires vocabulary before experience, not after experience only.

The claim that a named framework triggers “consulting theater” is too broad. Bad framework slides do that. A compact operating model does not. PME/ETI executives routinely work with named concepts when those concepts help them brief teams, assign ownership, and evaluate risk.

**Risks In The Failure-First Design**

- A staged failure can read as manipulation: “you intentionally made it bad, then fixed your own setup.”
- Four failure-fix loops in 30 minutes is too many. The room may remember the drama, not the transferable method.
- “Run it once with no SSI Monday” is dangerous advice. It normalizes unscoped agent use as the starting ritual.
- Making the framework “unphotographable” is backwards for executives. They need something photographable because their next task is delegation.
- The verifier role is useful, but too narrow. Adoption also needs task selection, reusable assets, governance, data boundaries, and team routines.
- Tool-agnosticism is not a teacher’s worry. It is exactly what an executive cares about before investing organizational energy in a workflow.

**Better Alternative**

Use concepts as a visible spine, but make them brutally minimal. Not a framework lecture. A map.

Open with one sentence:

> “An agent becomes useful when you split the work, give it memory, reuse the process, and verify against criteria.”

That is the whole SSI frame upfront. Then every manipulation hangs on it.

**30-Min Structure I’d Use**

- **0:00-2:00**: The four moves, named once: segmenter, mémoriser, réutiliser, vérifier.
- **2:00-7:00**: Show a weak generic memo attempt. Not a theatrical crash, just recognizable insufficiency.
- **7:00-14:00**: Apply segmentation and sources. Show the output improving.
- **14:00-20:00**: Turn the improved process into a reusable workflow/repository artifact.
- **20:00-26:00**: Put the executive in verifier mode with acceptance criteria.
- **26:00-30:00**: Give the transfer sheet: “When piloting a team use case, ask these four questions.”

**Minimum Viable Explicitation**

One slide at the beginning, one sheet at the end, same four words.

Not definitions. Questions:

- **Segmentation**: What should the agent do in separate steps?
- **External memory**: What sources must it use?
- **Repository**: What should be reusable next time?
- **Packaging / verification**: What criteria decide acceptance?

That earns its place because it gives executives language they can reuse with teams. The live demo supplies belief. The concept map supplies transfer. Without both, the session risks being memorable but not deployable.

## Round 2 — Agent A

# Proposing side, round 2: Concede the structure, fight the order, sharpen the demo.

## What the reviewer got right (and I'm taking)
- **Four loops is too many.** Granted. Two felt moments plus two narrated ones is the right cadence for 30 min.
- **"Monday with no SSI" was reckless.** Replace with: *Monday, pick one recurring task and answer the four questions on paper before launching anything.* That preserves transfer without normalizing unscoped use.
- **Verifier-only is too narrow.** Task selection, reusable assets, data boundaries belong in the frame. The verifier moment is one of four, not the whole show.
- **Tool-agnosticism matters to buyers.** Conceded for the *concept layer*. Still contested for the *belief layer* (see below).
- **The four words as questions, not nouns, is a real upgrade over my version.** Questions are delegation-ready in a way definitions aren't. Steal that.

## Where the reviewer overcorrected
- **"Vocabulary before experience" inverts the causal arrow that actually works in 30 min.** Executives don't lack vocabulary. They lack a *sensory anchor* for which vocabulary is load... is doing the work versus which is decoration. Name the four words at 0:00, fine. But the words remain inert until a felt moment binds them. The reviewer's plan names them at 0:00 *and* expects them to do the binding work *and* serves them as the takeaway sheet. Same artifact, three jobs. It will do one of them well.
- **"Recognizable insufficiency" is not the same lesson as visible failure.** A weak generic memo is the demo every consultant gives. Executives have seen ten of those and concluded "AI is meh." The point of staged friction is not drama, it is rupture of the *polished-demo prior* they walk in with. Without that rupture, the four words become another framework they nod at and forget.
- **"Staged failure reads as manipulation" is a real risk but solvable by transparency, not avoidance.** Say it out loud at minute 4: *"I gave it a prompt your team would actually write on a Tuesday. This is what you'll get. Now watch what changes."* That neutralizes the manipulation read and turns the failure into a mirror of their own team's first attempt, which is precisely the adoption risk they came to manage.
- **"Photographable framework" assumption is doing work it shouldn't.** Execs don't delegate from photographs. They delegate from a one-page brief their assistant typed up Monday morning after they described what they saw. The leave-behind sheet is the photographable artifact. The opening slide does not need to be.
- **Tool-agnosticism at the belief layer cuts the wrong way.** An exec who has not seen Cowork (or any concrete tool) produce a deployable artifact in front of them will not authorize budget for *any* tool. Belief is tool-specific. Transfer is tool-agnostic. The session needs both, in that order.

## Where the reviewer's own plan is fragile
- **Zero buffer.** 30 minutes with four named acts and a live tool has no recovery slot if Cowork stalls, a PDF won't upload, or the model gives an off-topic answer. My version absorbed slippage into the failure-fix structure. The reviewer's does not. One bad API call and the spine breaks.
- **Verifier seat compressed to a 6-min window at 20:00-26:00.** If task selection and acceptance criteria are co-equal executive jobs, they need threading from minute 7 onward, not a single late block. The reviewer praised the verifier role then quietly demoted it.
- **No moment where the executive's own judgment is visibly required.** All four blocks are presenter-driven. The transfer sheet at minute 26 lands on a passive room.

## Synthesis: the version I'd actually run

**0:00-1:30 — Four questions, not four nouns.** One slide. The reviewer's question phrasing, kept. No definitions, no acronym, no "framework." Frame it as *"the four questions a team needs to answer before launching any agent task."* This is the photographable artifact for delegation.

**1:30-6:00 — The realistic first try.** Run the memo task with a prompt their team would write. Narrate honest... narrate what you did and didn't tell the agent. Let the output land as recognizably insufficient *and* visibly wrong on one specific fact. Both registers. Generic prose alone won't move them; one wrong revenue figure will.

**6:00-13:00 — Segmentation and sources, executive-driven.** Ask the room: *"Which question did we skip?"* They will say segmentation or sources. Apply their answer. Re-run. This is the verifier seat starting early, not waiting until minute 20.

**13:00-19:00 — Reusable artifact.** Save prompt plus acceptance criteria as a workflow. Run it on a second input chosen by someone in the room. This is where tool-specificity earns belief and tool-agnosticism gets named: *"What you just saw works in Claude Code and Codex CLI too. The four questions are the portable part."*

**19:00-25:00 — Acceptance criteria as the executive job.** Hand them the second output. Ask: *"Would you sign off? On what?"* Let the silence work. This is the moment that converts to Monday behavior.

**25:00-28:00 — Transfer sheet.** Four questions, four demo memories, one Monday instruction: *answer the four questions on paper before your team launches anything.*

**28:00-30:00 — Buffer / Q&A / tool recovery.** Non-negotiable.

## The actual disagreement, named
- Reviewer's model: **language enables delegation, demo supplies belief, both delivered cleanly.**
- My model: **felt rupture enables belief, language enables delegation, sequencing matters because abstract priors block sensory updates.**
- The synthesis above keeps the reviewer's question-framing and minimal slide, keeps my staged-insufficiency and early verifier seat, and adds a buffer the reviewer's plan lacks. That's a stronger course than either pure version, and it's still 30 minutes.

## One thing I'd still argue against if pushed
- **Naming the acronym "SSI" out loud in the room.** The four questions are the deliverable. The acronym is for the slide deck you email afterward. In the room it adds zero and signals trainer-jargon. Sell the questions, not the brand.

## Round 2 — Agent B

This round is much stronger. The synthesis is close to the right answer: minimal conceptual frame up front, felt proof in the middle, transfer artifact at the end.

But I’d still challenge three assumptions.

**1. Be careful with “visible wrong fact”**

A wrong revenue figure is memorable, but it can backfire. Executives may conclude: “This tool invents numbers, so my teams should not touch it.” The failure should be real enough to matter, but not so catastrophic that it becomes the takeaway.

Better failure:

- wrong prioritization
- missing caveat
- generic recommendation
- unsupported claim
- no traceability to sources
- unclear decision criteria

For this audience, “the agent sounds plausible but cannot be signed off” is the more useful failure than “the agent hallucinated a hard number.” It points directly to the executive role: acceptance, governance, and delegation.

**2. The four questions should appear before the demo, but not as a slide to teach**

I agree with the order: four questions first, demo second. But the opening artifact should be framed as a diagnostic lens, not a lesson.

For example:

> “While I run the demo, watch for which of these questions we failed to answer.”

That makes the room active from minute one. The questions become a scorecard for the demo, not an abstract framework.

The slide could be:

- What should be split?
- What must the agent know?
- What should be reusable?
- What proves the result is acceptable?

No acronym. No SSI label. No definitions.

**3. The second input chosen by the room is risky**

Letting someone choose the second input sounds participatory, but in 30 minutes it adds variance. They may pick something too vague, too sensitive, too complex, or impossible to process live.

A better version: offer two pre-cleared second inputs and let the room choose.

> “Do we test the workflow on a supplier-risk note or on a hiring-plan note?”

They still feel agency, but you control the blast radius.

**The strongest version I’d run**

0:00-1:30  
Show the four questions. Tell them: “Your job is to catch which question is missing.”

1:30-5:30  
Run the realistic first attempt. It should be plausible but not signable: generic, under-sourced, weakly structured, no acceptance criteria.

5:30-11:00  
Ask the room which question failed first. Apply segmentation and sources. Re-run a focused piece.

11:00-16:30  
Turn the improved prompt, source list, and criteria into a reusable workflow artifact. This is the “not just a chat” moment.

16:30-22:30  
Run the workflow on a second pre-cleared input. Put the room in sign-off mode: “What would make this acceptable enough to send to a CODIR member?”

22:30-26:00  
Name the portable model: the tool is Cowork, the operating discipline is the four questions. Mention that the same discipline applies in Claude Code, Codex CLI, or future tools.

26:00-28:00  
Hand out the transfer sheet: four questions, four demo memories, one Monday instruction.

28:00-30:00  
Buffer or one question.

**On “SSI”**

I agree: do not say “SSI” during the live workshop unless the audience has already bought into the program language elsewhere. In-room, the four questions are stronger. “SSI” can exist in the post-session PDF as the internal name of the method.

The best framing is not “concepts versus manipulations.” It is:

> Give them a lens before the demo, a failure they can diagnose, and a portable checklist after the demo.

That keeps the conceptual spine without making the workshop feel like framework theater.

## Round 3 — Agent A

# Proposing side, round 3: Mostly conceded, three refinements, one open question.

## Concessions (taken whole)
- **Soft failure beats sharp failure for this audience.** "Plausible but unsignable" is the right register. Wrong-number failure tips into "the tool is dangerous" rather than "the tool needs discipline." Reviewer wins this cleanly.
- **Questions as diagnostic scorecard, not lesson.** The "watch for which question we failed to answer" framing is better than my "felt rupture" version. It makes the room active without requiring shock.
- **Pre-cleared second inputs with a choice between two.** Right call. Variance control without losing agency.
- **No "SSI" in the room.** Settled. The acronym lives in the post-session PDF, the questions live in the workshop.

## Three refinements that still earn their weight

**1. The soft failure needs one diagnosable miss, not just general mush.**

If the first attempt is uniformly generic and under-sourced, the room may shrug. Executives have approved plenty of generic memos. For the scorecard to activate, the output should *visibly* fail exactly one of the four questions in a way the room can point at. My recommendation: under-sourced (fails question 2: "what must the agent know?") and missing acceptance criteria (fails question 4). Two questions visibly missed, two questions partially answered. That gives the room something to *diagnose* rather than just *evaluate*.

**2. Rephrase the diagnostic prompt from "which question failed" to "which one would you fix first?"**

A realistic first attempt misses several questions at once. "Which failed first" forces wrong precision and may stall the room. "Which would you fix first?" is itself an executive skill (prioritization under partial failure), and it routes the answer toward action rather than scoring.

**3. Name portability *during* the workflow-saving moment, not at 22:30.**

The reviewer's 22:30-26:00 block names the portable model after the second demo. By then execs are mentally drafting Monday and only half-listening. The natural moment to say "this would work in any tool that lets you save a prompt plus criteria" is around 13:00-14:00, when the abstraction becomes concretely visible as you click Save on the workflow. The portability claim lands harder when paired with the visible artifact than when delivered as a closing remark.

## Open question worth naming
- **The two canonical examples have collapsed into one.** The original brief listed (a) the strategic memo and (b) a reusable workflow for a recurring task. The current synthesis folds (b) into (a) by saving the memo prompt as a workflow and rerunning on a second input. I think this consolidation is right for a 30-min slot. One worked example carrying both lessons is stronger than two half-developed examples. But it should be a deliberate choice, not an accident. If the leave-behind PDF is meant to seed two distinct use cases in the org, the second one needs at least a paragraph there, even if it doesn't get demo time.

## Operational notes the plan still needs
- **Backup screenshot of the first failure.** The highest-variance moment is minute 1:30-5:30: if Cowork produces something accidentally good or accidentally incomprehensible, the diagnostic scorecard doesn't activate. Pre-record a fallback screenshot of a known-insufficient output, and be willing to switch to it if the live run misbehaves.
- **Transfer sheet on paper, not a QR code.** PME/ETI execs photograph paper with their phone and forward it to their assistant Monday morning. That is the actual transfer mechanism. A QR code linking to a Notion page will get lost.
- **Monday instruction, tightened.** Reviewer accepted "answer the four questions on paper before launching anything." I'd add one more constraint: *with a colleague in the verifier seat.* That introduces the proposer/verifier split into the org without requiring any tool sophistication. The single most useful import from the workshop is not the four questions, it is the two-seat structure that the four questions enable.

## Resolved frame
- **Lens before the demo, failure they can diagnose, sign-off moment in the middle, portability named when it becomes visible, checklist after.** That's the spine. Concepts and manipulations stop being a dichotomy because the concepts are delivered as questions the demo answers and the manipulations are delivered as diagnostic moments the questions structure.

## Where I think we're done
- The structural disagreement (concepts-as-spine vs manipulations-as-spine) is dissolved. The right answer is neither: it is **diagnostic questions as scaffolding for a worked example**, with the questions doing the conceptual work and the worked example doing the belief work. Both layers, one artifact, 30 minutes, with the verifier seat introduced as the Monday transfer rather than as the workshop's main act.

## Round 3 — Agent B

The unresolved issue is real: if the memo example absorbs the workflow example, the session may become “how to make a better memo” instead of “how to pilot agent work.” That is the main risk now.

**Concrete choice:** use **one consolidated live example**, not two. But make the reusable workflow artifact visible as a management object, not just a saved Cowork prompt.

In the live 30 minutes, show:

1. A plausible but unsignable memo attempt.
2. The four diagnostic questions used to improve it.
3. The saved workflow as a reusable **agent task brief**.
4. A second pre-cleared input to prove reuse.
5. A short delegation and governance drill.

Do **not** run a second canonical example live. Thirty minutes cannot support two examples, participation, tool variance, and governance. Two live examples will make both shallow.

The leave-behind should carry the second canonical example: “recurring workflow automation.” Give it as a fully written case with before/after, sample task brief, acceptance criteria, verifier role, and data boundary.

**What belongs live**

Live should only contain what must be felt or seen:

- The insufficiency of a naive agent run.
- The executive act of choosing what to fix first.
- The effect of sources, segmentation, and criteria.
- The fact that a prompt can become a reusable operating asset.
- The proposer/verifier split as a team routine.

Add one governance moment, not a governance section:

> “Before a team launches this, who proposes, who verifies, what data is allowed, and what output is not allowed to leave the room?”

That earns its place because it turns the demo into delegation.

**What belongs in the leave-behind**

The leave-behind should do the heavy transfer work:

- The four questions.
- The memo example recap.
- A separate recurring-workflow example.
- A one-page pilot brief template.
- A lightweight governance checklist: owner, verifier, data boundary, source list, acceptance criteria, escalation rule.
- A Monday instruction: pick one recurring task, write the pilot brief with a verifier, then run one controlled attempt.

The non-obvious point: the artifact they should leave with is not “SSI” and not “a Cowork workflow.” It is the **pilot brief**. That is what executives can delegate, review, and govern.

So the architecture is:

> One live example for belief. One pilot brief for delegation. One leave-behind for transfer.

## Round 4 — Agent A

# Proposing side, round 4: Architecture accepted. Risk closure and final run-of-show.

## Accept
The architecture **"one live example for belief, one pilot brief for delegation, one leave-behind for transfer"** is accepted as the final frame. The second canonical example moves to the leave-behind. The pilot brief becomes the delegable artifact. The four questions remain the in-room conceptual spine.

## Risk closure

**Risk A: Can the pilot brief be explained fast enough?**

Yes, if it is introduced as the *written form of the four questions*, not as a new artifact. The brief has six fields: task, owner, verifier, data boundary, sources, acceptance criteria. Four of those map directly onto the four questions; the other two (owner, data boundary) are the governance overlay. Introduce it once on screen at minute 14, partially filled from the live demo, with one sentence: *"This is what the four questions look like when a team writes them down before launching."* No new vocabulary, no new framework. Total airtime: ~90 seconds.

**Risk B: Does the governance moment crowd the demo?**

It will if it becomes a discussion. The mitigation is to ask the governance question once, accept one or two voices, then route the rest to the leave-behind checklist. Specifically: at minute 22, ask the four sub-questions (proposer, verifier, data, what does not leave the room) as a single prompt. Take two answers. Say: *"The full checklist is on page 2 of the sheet you'll get."* Move on. If the room wants RGPD discussion (likely for French PME), name that explicitly as out of scope for the 30-min slot and offer a follow-up. Total airtime: 3 minutes, capped.

**Risk C: What exact output do executives delegate on Monday?**

The pilot brief. Not "the four questions on paper" (too abstract), not "run a Cowork workflow" (tool-specific), not "experiment with agents" (unscoped). One filled pilot brief per recurring task they want to pilot, with a named verifier inside the org, run once under supervision before any normalization. The brief is the unit a team lead can act on and a director can review. That is the deliverable.

## Final 30-min run-of-show

| Time | Block | What happens |
|---|---|---|
| 0:00-1:30 | Frame | Show the four questions. Tell the room: "Your job is to catch which one we fail to answer." No acronym, no definitions. |
| 1:30-5:30 | First attempt | Run the realistic prompt. Output is plausible but visibly under-sourced and missing acceptance criteria. Backup screenshot ready. |
| 5:30-10:30 | Diagnostic | Ask: "Which would you fix first?" Apply segmentation and sources from the room's answer. Re-run a focused piece. |
| 10:30-14:00 | Save as reusable | Save prompt plus criteria. Name portability here: "This shape works in any tool that lets you save a prompt and criteria." |
| 14:00-15:30 | Pilot brief reveal | Show the brief on screen, partially filled from the live demo. One sentence: "The four questions, written down for a team." |
| 15:30-21:30 | Reuse on second input | Two pre-cleared options, room chooses one. Run. Output should be visibly stronger because the brief constrains it. |
| 21:30-24:30 | Sign-off and governance | "Would you sign off? On what?" Then the four sub-questions: proposer, verifier, data boundary, what does not leave. Two answers. Route rest to the sheet. |
| 24:30-27:30 | Transfer | Hand out the leave-behind. Monday instruction: "Pick one recurring task. Fill the brief with a named verifier. Run one supervised attempt." |
| 27:30-30:00 | Buffer | One question or recovery time. Non-negotiable. |

